## 860                1
## 863                1
data$JobLevel = as.factor(data$JobLevel)
# List of columns you want to calculate percentages for
columns_of_interest <- c("BusinessTravel", "Department", "Education", "EducationField", "EnvironmentSatisfaction","Gender", "JobInvolvement","JobLevel", "JobRole","JobSatisfaction","MaritalStatus", "OverTime")


# Initialize a list to store the result dataframes for each column
result_dfs <- list()

# Loop through each column
for (col in columns_of_interest) {
  # Check if the column exists in the dataframe
  if (col %in% names(data)) {
    # Remove missing values from the column
    data_subset <- na.omit(data[, c(col, "Attrition")])
    
    # Calculate the table of counts for each combination of the current column and Attrition
    attrition_counts <- table(data_subset[[col]], data_subset$Attrition)
    
    # Get unique values of the current column
    unique_values <- unique(data_subset[[col]])
    
    # Initialize vector to store percentages
    percentage_yes <- numeric(length(unique_values))
    
    # Calculate the percentage of "Yes" attrition for each unique value in the current column
    for (i in 1:length(unique_values)) {
      value <- unique_values[i]
      total_count <- sum(attrition_counts[value, ])
      if (length(attrition_counts[value, "Yes"]) > 0) {
        yes_count <- attrition_counts[value, "Yes"]
        percentage_yes[i] <- (yes_count / total_count) * 100
      } else {
        percentage_yes[i] <- 0
      }
    }
    
    # Create a dataframe to store the results for the current column
    result_df <- data.frame(Value = unique_values, Percentage_Yes = percentage_yes)
    result_df$Column <- col
    
    # Append the result dataframe to the list
    result_dfs[[col]] <- result_df
  } else {
    print(paste("Column", col, "does not exist in the dataframe."))
  }
}

# Combine all result dataframes into a single dataframe
final_result <- do.call(rbind, result_dfs)

# Print the final result dataframe
print(final_result)

# Create a bar plot for each column
plots <- lapply(unique(final_result$Column), function(col) {
  ggplot(subset(final_result, Column == col), aes(x = Value, y = Percentage_Yes, fill = Value)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    labs(title = paste("Percentage of 'Yes' Attrition for", col),
         x = col, y = "Percentage of 'Yes' Attrition") +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
})

# Print the plots
print(plots)

# Function to calculate proportions of "Yes" for each category level
calculate_attrition_proportions <- function(variable) {
  proportions <- table(filtered_yes[[variable]]) / nrow(filtered_yes)
  return(proportions)
}

# Apply the function to each categorical variable in your dataset
categorical_variables <- c("BusinessTravel", "Department", "Education", "EducationField", "EnvironmentSatisfaction","Gender", "JobInvolvement","JobLevel", "JobRole","JobSatisfaction","MaritalStatus", "OverTime")  # List of your categorical variables
attrition_proportions <- lapply(categorical_variables, calculate_attrition_proportions)

# Print the proportions for each category level
names(attrition_proportions) <- categorical_variables  # Assign names to the list
print(attrition_proportions)

# Assuming 'data' is your dataframe
# Load necessary libraries for visualization
library(ggplot2)

# Define the continuous variable you want to visualize
continuous_variable <- "Age"  # Replace with the name of your continuous variable

# Define the number of bins for the histogram
num_bins <- 10  # You can adjust this value based on your preference

# Bin the continuous variable into intervals
data$bin <- cut(data[[continuous_variable]], breaks = num_bins, include.lowest = TRUE)

# Calculate the percentage of "Yes" attrition for each interval
attrition_percentages <- aggregate(Attrition ~ bin, data = data, FUN = function(x) {
  yes_count <- sum(x == "Yes")
  total_count <- length(x)
  return((yes_count / total_count) * 100)
})

# Create a histogram
histogram <- ggplot(attrition_percentages, aes(x = bin, y = Attrition)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = paste("Percentage of 'Yes' Attrition for", continuous_variable),
       x = continuous_variable, y = "Percentage of 'Yes' Attrition") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

# Print the histogram
print(histogram)

# Assuming 'data' is your dataframe
# Load necessary libraries for visualization
library(ggplot2)

# Define the continuous variables you want to visualize
continuous_variables <- c("Age", "MonthlyIncome","DailyRate","NumCompaniesWorked","PercentSalaryHike","PerformanceRating","RelationshipSatisfaction", "TotalWorkingYears")  # Replace with the names of your continuous variables

# Define the number of bins for the histogram
num_bins <- 10  # You can adjust this value based on your preference

# Initialize a list to store the histograms
histograms <- list()

# Loop through each continuous variable
for (continuous_variable in continuous_variables) {
  # Bin the continuous variable into intervals
  data$bin <- cut(data[[continuous_variable]], breaks = num_bins, include.lowest = TRUE)
  
  # Calculate the percentage of "Yes" attrition for each interval
  attrition_percentages <- aggregate(Attrition ~ bin, data = data, FUN = function(x) {
    yes_count <- sum(x == "Yes")
    total_count <- length(x)
    return((yes_count / total_count) * 100)
  })
  
  # Create a histogram
  histogram <- ggplot(attrition_percentages, aes(x = bin, y = Attrition)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    labs(title = paste("Percentage of 'Yes' Attrition for", continuous_variable),
         x = continuous_variable, y = "Percentage of 'Yes' Attrition") +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
  
  # Append the histogram to the list
  histograms[[continuous_variable]] <- histogram
}

# Print the histograms
for (i in 1:length(histograms)) {
  print(histograms[[i]])
}

#classification model for attrition 
# Step 1: Load required libraries
library(e1071) # For Naive Bayes classifier
library(caret) # For data preprocessing and evaluation
## Loading required package: lattice
# Step 2: Only top correlated varibles in data
classification_variables <- c("Attrition","JobLevel", "MonthlyIncome", "JobRole", "Age")

# Subset the dataset to include only the selected variables
classification_data <- data[, classification_variables]
classification_data$Attrition <- as.factor(classification_data$Attrition)



# Step 4: Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123) # For reproducibility
train_indices <- sample(1:nrow(classification_data), 0.78 * nrow(classification_data))  # 70% training data
train_data <- classification_data[train_indices, ]
test_data <- classification_data[-train_indices, ]

# Step 5: Train the Naive Bayes model
model_NB <- naiveBayes(Attrition ~ ., data = train_data)

# Step 6: Make predictions on the test set
predictions <- predict(model_NB, test_data, type = "raw")
#predictions
preds = ifelse(predictions[,1] > .75,"No", "Yes") #harder to be no
#class(preds)


preds = as.factor(preds)
#class(preds)
#preds
conf_matrix <- confusionMatrix(preds, test_data$Attrition)
conf_matrix

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)
data$JobLevel = as.factor(data$JobLevel)

# Create an index for train-test split
train_index <- sample(1:nrow(data), 0.7 * nrow(data))  # 70% for training, adjust as needed

# Split the data into training and testing sets
train_data <- data[train_index, ]
test_data <- data[-train_index, ]

# Fit multiple linear regression model using only training data
model_lm <- lm(MonthlyIncome ~ JobLevel + JobRole + TotalWorkingYears, data = train_data)

# Predict the target variable using the model on test data
predicted <- predict(model_lm, newdata = test_data)

# Calculate RMSE
rmse <- sqrt(mean((predicted - test_data$MonthlyIncome)^2))

# Print RMSE
print(rmse)

# Building a Shiny App for Job specific trends
library(ggplot2)
library(shiny)

# Define UI
ui <- fluidPage(
  titlePanel("Analysis on Job Specific Roles"),
  
  sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
      selectInput("plotType", "Select Analysis Type:",
                  choices = c("Gender analysis", "Income vs Working years analysis", "Job satisfaction analysis"))
    ),
    
    mainPanel(
      uiOutput("selectedPlot")
    )
  )
)

# Define server logic
server <- function(input, output) {
  
  output$selectedPlot <- renderUI({
    plotType <- input$plotType
    
    if (plotType == "Gender analysis") {
      plotOutput("plot1")
    } else if (plotType == "Income vs Working years analysis") {
      plotOutput("plot2")
    } else if (plotType == "Job satisfaction analysis") {
      plotOutput("plot3")
    }
  })
  
  output$plot1 <- renderPlot({
    # Create Plot 1 (replace with your plot code)
    ggplot(data, aes(x = JobRole, fill = Gender)) +
    geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
    labs(x = "Job Role", y = "Count", fill = "Gender") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
  })
  
  output$plot2 <- renderPlot({
    # Create Plot 2 (replace with your plot code)
    ggplot(data, aes(x =MonthlyIncome, y = TotalWorkingYears, color = JobRole)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(x = "Monthly Income", y = "Total Working Years", color = "Job Role")
  })
  
  output$plot3 <- renderPlot({
    # Create Plot 3 (replace with your plot code)
    ggplot(data, aes(x = JobSatisfaction, fill = JobLevel)) +
      geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, position = "dodge") +
      labs(x = "Job Satisfaction", y = "Frequency", fill = "Job Level") +
      facet_wrap(~JobRole) +
      scale_fill_manual(values = c("1" = "blue", "2" = "green", "3" = "red", "4" = "orange")) +  #Customize colors
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
  })
}

# Run the application
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)
